  <header class="hero">
    <span class="hero-eyebrow">Protein After 60</span>
    <h1>How Much Protein Do Men Over 60<br><span class="green">Actually Need?</span></h1>
    <p class="hero-sub">By 60, the muscle you still have is harder to keep — and significantly harder to rebuild once it's gone. The protein target shifts upward, and so does the urgency for getting it right.</p>
    <p style="color:#6ee7a0;font-family:'Plus Jakarta Sans',sans-serif;font-weight:700;font-size:1rem;margin-top:1rem;">Most men aren't low on effort — they're low on protein.</p>
    <p class="hero-meta">SnapProtein &nbsp;·&nbsp; 8 min read</p>
  </header>

  <!-- ARTICLE BODY -->
  <div class="container">
    <article>

      <!-- AUTHOR NOTE -->
      <div class="author-note">
        <div class="author-avatar">R</div>
        <p><strong>A note from Robert:</strong> I'm 64. I'm not writing this from a textbook — I'm writing it from inside the demographic this post is about. At this age, the difference between men who are strong and independent and men who are struggling isn't mostly genetics. It's mostly protein and resistance training, compounded over years. This is the number I wish more men in their 60s knew.</p>
      </div>

      <!-- QUICK ANSWER -->
      <div class="quick-answer">
        <h2>Quick Answer</h2>
        <ul>
          <li>Men over 60 need <strong>1.4–1.8 g of protein per kilogram of bodyweight per day</strong> — the highest target on the age ladder</li>
          <li>For a 185-pound (84 kg) man, that's <strong>118–150g of protein daily</strong></li>
          <li>The target is higher than for men in their 40s because <strong>anabolic resistance increases with age</strong> — your muscles need a bigger protein signal to respond</li>
          <li>Aim for <strong>35–45g per meal</strong> across 3–4 meals — slightly higher per-meal doses than younger men due to reduced muscle sensitivity</li>
          <li>Muscle lost after 60 is <strong>significantly harder to rebuild</strong> than at younger ages — protecting what you have is the priority</li>
        </ul>
      </div>

      <!-- SECTION 1 -->
      <div class="section">
        <h2>Your 60s Are Different — Here's Why the Number Goes Up</h2>
        <p>Men in their 40s are at the beginning of a biological shift. Men in their 50s are in the middle of it. By 60, that shift is well established — and the stakes are higher.</p>
        <p>The core issue is anabolic resistance: the progressive decline in your muscles' ability to respond to protein. At 25, a moderate protein meal triggered strong muscle protein synthesis. At 45, it took a bit more. By 65, it takes meaningfully more — and the window between "enough to maintain" and "not enough" has narrowed considerably.</p>
        <p>This is why the research-backed target for men over 60 is higher than for men over 40. It's not pessimism — it's precision. The system still works. It just requires more precision than it used to.</p>

        <div class="callout">
          <h3>What the research actually shows</h3>
          <p>Multiple large studies on protein needs in older adults — including work published in the <em>Journal of the American Medical Directors Association</em> — support intakes of <strong>1.4–1.8 g/kg/day</strong> for men over 60, particularly those who are active. The standard RDA of 0.8 g/kg was set to prevent deficiency in sedentary young adults. It was never designed for muscle preservation in aging men.</p>
        </div>
      </div>

      <!-- SECTION 2 — AGE LADDER -->
      <div class="section">
        <h2>The Age Ladder: How Protein Needs Shift Over Time</h2>
        <p>Your protein requirements don't jump overnight — they rise gradually as anabolic resistance increases. Here's how the targets compare across decades, and where men over 60 sit on that progression.</p>

        <div class="age-ladder">
          <div class="age-card">
            <div class="ac-label">Over 40</div>
            <div class="ac-target">1.2–1.6 g/kg/day<br>~100–130g for 185 lb</div>
          </div>
          <div class="age-card">
            <div class="ac-label">Over 50</div>
            <div class="ac-target">1.3–1.7 g/kg/day<br>~110–143g for 185 lb</div>
          </div>
          <div class="age-card active">
            <div class="ac-label">Over 60 ← You</div>
            <div class="ac-target">1.4–1.8 g/kg/day<br>~118–150g for 185 lb</div>
          </div>
        </div>

        <p style="font-size:0.93rem;color:var(--text-muted);margin:0.75rem 0 1.4rem;font-style:italic;">The difference isn't dramatic year to year — but over a decade, it adds up.</p>

        <table class="data-table">
          <thead>
            <tr>
              <th>Bodyweight</th>
              <th>RDA (0.8 g/kg) — minimum</th>
              <th>Recommended (1.6 g/kg) — target</th>
            </tr>
          </thead>
          <tbody>
            <tr>
              <td>160 lb (73 kg)</td>
              <td>58g/day</td>
              <td>117g/day</td>
            </tr>
            <tr class="highlight-row">
              <td>185 lb (84 kg)</td>
              <td>67g/day</td>
              <td>134g/day</td>
            </tr>
            <tr>
              <td>200 lb (91 kg)</td>
              <td>73g/day</td>
              <td>146g/day</td>
            </tr>
            <tr>
              <td>220 lb (100 kg)</td>
              <td>80g/day</td>
              <td>160g/day</td>
            </tr>
          </tbody>
        </table>
        <p style="font-size:0.82rem;color:var(--text-muted);">Highlighted row = common weight for men in their 60s. Use 1.4 g/kg as a conservative floor and 1.8 g/kg if you're lifting regularly. The RDA is a deficiency threshold, not a performance target.</p>

        <div class="related-link">
          <span class="rl-icon">🔗</span>
          <p>How the over-50 target compares: <a href="https://snapprotein.com/blog/protein-after-50/">How Much Protein Do Men Over 50 Actually Need?</a></p>
        </div>
      </div>

      <!-- SECTION 3 -->
      <div class="section">
        <h2>What Happens When Men Over 60 Don't Hit Their Target</h2>
        <p>This isn't abstract. Chronic low protein intake in men over 60 has measurable, compounding consequences — and they accelerate the longer the gap persists.</p>

        <h3>Accelerated sarcopenia</h3>
        <p>Sarcopenia — age-related muscle loss — progresses at roughly 1–2% per year after 50 without intervention. Chronically low protein intake can accelerate that rate significantly. The downstream effects include reduced grip strength, slower walking speed, and increasing difficulty with activities that were effortless a decade ago.</p>

        <h3>Higher fall risk</h3>
        <p>Falls are the leading cause of injury-related death in adults over 65. Muscle strength — particularly in the legs and core — is the primary protective factor. Muscle mass requires adequate protein to maintain. The connection is direct and well-documented.</p>
        <p>This isn't about gym performance — it's about staying independent.</p>

        <h3>Slower recovery</h3>
        <p>After any illness, injury, or surgery, the body draws heavily on muscle protein to fuel the repair process. Men over 60 with low muscle reserves recover more slowly, lose more muscle during recovery, and have a harder time rebuilding afterward. Protein adequacy before a health event matters — you can't stockpile it at the time.</p>

        <h3>Metabolic slowdown</h3>
        <p>Muscle is metabolically active tissue. Less of it means a slower resting metabolism, which makes weight management harder and compounds the effects of aging on energy levels and body composition.</p>

        <div class="callout">
          <h3>The asymmetry that matters most</h3>
          <p>At 60+, the math on muscle is asymmetric: <strong>losing it is easy, gaining it back is hard</strong>. A month of illness or low activity can cost muscle that takes months to rebuild — if it comes back at all. This is why protection is the priority, and why the protein target at this age is not optional.</p>
        </div>
      </div>

      <!-- SECTION 4 — TESTIMONIAL -->
      <div class="section">
        <h2>Still Performing at 60+ — What It Actually Takes</h2>
        <p>The men who stay strong, lean, and physically capable into their 60s and 70s aren't genetic outliers. They've built systems — and protein is usually a central part of those systems.</p>

