        <h2>How to Hit the Target: Practical Framework for Men Over 60</h2>
        <p>The target is higher than most men expect. But the system for hitting it doesn't have to be complicated.</p>

        <h3>Work backward from 35–45g per meal</h3>
        <p>At this age, per-meal protein doses matter more than at younger ages. Due to increased anabolic resistance, you need a larger protein stimulus per meal to reliably trigger muscle protein synthesis. Aim for 35–45g per meal rather than the 30g that's often cited for younger men. Three meals hitting that range puts you in the 105–135g zone — right in the target.</p>

        <h3>Fix breakfast first — it's where most men lose 40g</h3>
        <p>Most men over 60 eat a carb-heavy breakfast — toast, cereal, oatmeal — and push the protein load to dinner. By then it's too late to distribute effectively, and a single large dose is less efficient than spread-out meals. A 35–40g breakfast changes the entire day's math. Most men never fix this — and it costs them 30–40 grams daily.</p>

        <h3>Anchor around 4–5 high-protein staples</h3>
        <p>Most men eat the same 8–12 foods regularly. Identify the 4–5 with the highest protein content that you actually enjoy, and build your meals around them. Chicken breast (35g), Greek yogurt (17–20g), eggs (6g each), cottage cheese (25g per cup), canned salmon (30g). You don't need variety — you need reliability.</p>

        <h3>Track for two weeks, then recalibrate</h3>
        <p>Most men over 60 who track protein for the first time are surprised by the gap — typically 30–50g below their target on an average day. Two weeks of honest logging closes that gap by making it visible. After that, you develop intuition that makes the habit sustainable without constant tracking.</p>

