        <h2>Is It Too Late? What the Research Says</h2>
        <p>This is the question men in their 60s most want answered honestly: is there still a point?</p>
        <p>The answer from the research is unambiguous: yes. Studies consistently show that men in their 60s and 70s can build meaningful muscle with resistance training and adequate protein. The rate of gain is slower than at younger ages, and the protein requirements are higher — but the capacity is real and well-documented.</p>
        <p>The goal at 60+ isn't the same as at 35. It's not about maximizing gains. It's about preserving what you have, rebuilding what you've lost, and maintaining the strength and independence that define quality of life in the decades ahead. All of that is achievable with the right inputs.</p>
        <p>The asymmetry, again: protection is cheap. Recovery is expensive. The men who are strong at 75 are almost always the men who made the protein habit a priority at 60 — not 70.</p>
